SIMPLE: tuck
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tuck
<hw>Tuck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>estoc</ets>; cf.
It. <ets>stocco</ets>; both of German origin, and akin to E.
<ets>stock</ets>. See <er>Stock</er>.]</ety> <def>A long, narrow sword;
a rapier.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He wore large hose, and a <qex>tuck</qex>, as it was then called,
or rapier, of tremendous length.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tuck
<hw>Tuck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Tocsin</er>.]</ety> <def>The
beat of a drum.</def> <rj><au>Scot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tuck
<hw>Tuck</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tucked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tucking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>tukken</ets>, LG.
<ets>tukken</ets> to pull up, tuck up, entice; akin to OD.
<ets>tocken</ets> to entice, G. <ets>zucken</ets> to draw with a short
and quick motion, and E. <ets>tug</ets>. See <er>Tug</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw up; to shorten; to fold under; to press into a
narrower compass; <as>as, to <ex>tuck</ex> the bedclothes in; to
<ex>tuck</ex> up one's sleeves.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make a tuck or tucks in; <as>as, to <ex>tuck</ex>
a dress</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To inclose; to put within; to press into a close
place; <as>as, to <ex>tuck</ex> a child into a bed; to <ex>tuck</ex> a
book under one's arm, or into a pocket.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <ety>[Perhaps originally, to strike, beat: cf. F.
<ets>toquer</ets> to touch. Cf. <er>Tocsin</er>.]</ety> <def>To full, as
cloth.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Tuck
<hw>Tuck</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To contract; to draw
together.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Tuck
<hw>Tuck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A horizontal sewed fold,
such as is made in a garment, to shorten it; a plait.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small net used for taking fish from a larger one;
-- called also <altname>tuck-net</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A pull; a lugging.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<see>See <er>Tug</er>.</see> <rj><au>Life of A. Wood.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The part of a vessel where the
ends of the bottom planks meet under the stern.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Food; pastry; sweetmeats.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
<rj><au>T. Hughes.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuckahoe</ent>⟦br⟧
